    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1899-12-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1899-12-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="641"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d641">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Stowe</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Cridler</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Consulate-General of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Cape Town</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1899-12-06">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 6, 1899</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 191.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to report that there arrived at
                    this port on September 6, on the way to Delagoa Bay, the Netherlands ship <hi
                        rend="italic">Maria</hi>, with cargo consisting largely of flour, canned
                    meats, and oats. The goods for the Transvaal were plainly marked. The ship was
                    detained by the British authorities, but finally was allowed to proceed.
                    Yesterday the British ship <hi rend="italic">Mashona</hi> was seized at Port
                    Elizabeth by H. M. S. <hi rend="italic">Partridge</hi>. The <hi rend="italic"
                        >Mashona</hi> was from New York, with 5,000 tons of general cargo, including
                    17,000 bags of flour for the Transvaal, via Delagoa Bay. She will probably be
                    brought to this port. Is food stuff, such as flour, contraband? Being a British
                    ship, has the British Government a right to seize?</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">J. G. Stowe</hi>,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">United States Consul-General.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
